of USS ''Monitor'']\n* [https://archive.org/details/DTIC_ADA033069 Project Cheesebox vol. 1]\n* [https://archive.org/details/DTIC_ADA033070/page/n1 Project Cheesebox vol. 2]\n*[https://archive.org/details/DTIC_ADA033071/page/n3 Project Cheesebox vol. 3]\n* {{cite web |url=http://oceanexplorer.noaa.gov/explorations/monitor01/monitor01.html |title=Preserving the USS ''Monitor'' 2001 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line--> |website=NOAA Ocean Explorer |date=March\u2013August 2001 |accessdate=24 February 2015 }}\n* {{cite web |url=http://oceanexplorer.noaa.gov/explorations/02monitor/welcome.html\n |title=''Monitor'' Expedition 2002 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line--> |website=NOAA Ocean Explorer |date=June\u2013December 2002 |accessdate=24 February 2015 }}\n\n{{Union ironclads}}\n{{Battle of Hampton Roads|state=autocollapse}}{{1862 shipwrecks}}{{National Register of Historic Places in North Carolina}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Monitor}}\n[[Category:American Civil War monitors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Dare County, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Battle of Hampton Roads]]\n[[Category:Shipwrecks of the Carolina coast]]\n[[Category:National Historic Landmarks in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Monitors of the United States Navy]]\n[[Category:Ships of the Union Navy]]\n[[Category:Shipwrecks of the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in December 1862]]\n[[Category:Shipwrecks on the National Register of Historic Places in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:1862 ships]]\n[[Category:Archaeology of shipwrecks]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Dare County, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Underwater archaeological sites]]\n[[Category:Underwater archaeology]]\n[[Category:Shipwrecks]]\n[[Category:Shipwrecks in the Atlantic Ocean]]\n[[Category:American Civil War on the National Register of Historic Places]]\n", "name_user": "222.153.59.222", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eBattle of Drewry's Bluff)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/USS_Monitor"}
{"title_page": "Debt deflation", "text_new": "'''Debt deflation''' is a theory that [[recession]]s and [[depression (economics)|depressions]] are due to the overall level of debt rising in real value because of deflation, causing people to default on their consumer loans and mortgages. Bank assets fall because of the defaults and because the value of their collateral falls, leading to a surge in bank insolvencies, a reduction in lending and by extension, a reduction in spending.\n\nThe theory was developed by [[Irving Fisher]] following the [[Wall Street Crash of 1929]] and the ensuing [[Great Depression]]. The debt deflation theory was familiar to [[John Maynard Keynes]] prior to Fisher's discussion of it, but he found it lacking in comparison to what would become his theory of [[liquidity preference]].<ref>Pilkington, Philip (February 24, 2014). \"[http://fixingtheeconomists.wordpress.com/2014/02/24/keynes-liquidity-preference-trumps-debt-deflation-in-1931-and-2008/ Keynes' Liquidity Preference Trumps Debt Deflation in 1931 and 2008]\".</ref> The theory, however, has enjoyed a resurgence of interest since the 1980s, both in [[mainstream economics]] and in the [[heterodox economics|heterodox]] school of [[post-Keynesian economics]], and has subsequently been developed by such post-Keynesian economists as [[Hyman Minsky]]<ref>Minsky, Hyman (1992). \"The Financial Instability Hypothesis\".</ref> and by the mainstream economist [[Ben Bernanke]].<ref>Steve Keen (1995). \"Finance and economic breakdown: modelling Minsky\u2019s Financial Instability Hypothesis\", ''Journal of Post Keynesian Economics'', Vol. 17, No. 4, 607&ndash;635</ref>\n\n== Fisher's formulation (1933) ==\nIn Fisher's formulation of debt [[deflation]], when the debt bubble bursts the following sequence of events occurs:\n{{quote\n|Assuming, accordingly, that, at some point in time, a state of over-indebtedness exists, this will tend to lead to liquidation, through the alarm either of debtors or creditors or both. Then we may deduce the following chain of consequences in nine links:\n# Debt liquidation leads to distress selling and to\n# Contraction of deposit currency, as bank loans are paid off, and to a slowing down of velocity of circulation. This contraction of deposits and of their velocity, precipitated by distress selling, causes\n# A fall in the level of prices, in other words, a swelling of the dollar. Assuming, as above stated, that this fall of prices is not interfered with by reflation or otherwise, there must be\n# A still greater fall in the net worths of business, precipitating bankruptcies and\n# A like fall in profits, which in a \"capitalistic,\" that is, a private-profit society, leads the concerns which are running at a loss to make\n# A reduction in output, in trade and in employment of labor. These losses, bankruptcies and unemployment, lead to\n# pessimism and loss of confidence, which in turn lead to\n# Hoarding and slowing down still more the velocity of circulation.\n#:The above eight changes cause\n# Complicated disturbances in the rates of interest, in particular, a fall in the nominal, or money, rates and a rise in the real, or commodity, rates of interest.\n|{{Harv|Fisher|1933}}}}\n\n=== Rejection of previous assumptions ===\nPrior to his theory of debt deflation, Fisher had subscribed to the then-prevailing, and still mainstream, theory of [[general equilibrium]]. In order to apply this to financial markets, which involve transactions across time in the form of debt \u2013 receiving money now in exchange for something in future \u2013 he made two further assumptions:<ref name=\"dw42\">[http://www.debtdeflation.com/blogs/2010/01/24/debtwatch-no-42-the-economic-case-against-bernanke/ Debtwatch No. 42: The economic case against Bernanke], January 24th, 2010, [[Steve Keen]]</ref>\n:(A) The [[Market clearing|market must be cleared]]\u2014and cleared with respect to every interval of time.\n:(B) The debts must be paid. {{Harv|Fisher|1930|loc=p.495}}\nIn view of the Depression, he rejected equilibrium, and noted that in fact debts might not be paid, but instead defaulted on:\n{{quote|It is as absurd to assume that, for any long period of time, the variables in the economic organization, or any part of them, will \"stay put,\" in perfect equilibrium, as to assume that the Atlantic Ocean can ever be without a wave.|{{Harv|Fisher|1933|loc=p. 339}}}}\nHe further rejected the notion that over-confidence alone, rather than the resulting debt, was a significant factor in the Depression:\n{{quote|I fancy that over-confidence seldom does any great harm except when, as, and if, it beguiles its victims into debt. | {{Harv|Fisher|1933|loc=p. 339}}}}\nIn the context of this quote and the development of his theory and the central role it places on debt, it is of note that Fisher was personally ruined due to his having assumed debt due to his over-confidence prior to the crash, by buying stocks on margin.\n\nOther debt deflation theories do not assume that debts must be paid, noting the role that default, bankruptcy, and foreclosure play in modern economies.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://libertyloveandjusticeforall.com/2012/12/08/debt-reset-is-inevitable/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-12-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130603123926/http://libertyloveandjusticeforall.com/2012/12/08/debt-reset-is-inevitable/ |archive-date=2013-06-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== Initial mainstream interest ===\nInitially Fisher's work was largely ignored, in favor of the work of Keynes.<ref name=\"shadow\">[http://www.economist.com/businessfinance/displaystory.cfm?story_id=13104022 Out of Keynes's shadow], [[The Economist]], Feb 12th 2009</ref>\n\nThe following decades saw occasional mention of deflationary spirals due to debt in the mainstream, notably in ''[[The Great Crash, 1929]]'' of [[John Kenneth Galbraith]] in 1954, and the [[credit cycle]] has occasionally been cited as a leading cause of economic cycles in the post-WWII era, as in {{harv|Eckstein|Sinai|1990}}, but private debt remained absent from mainstream macroeconomic models.\n\n[[James Tobin]] cited Fisher as instrumental in his theory of economic instability.\n\nDebt-deflation theory has been studied since the 1930s but was largely ignored by neoclassical economists, and has only recently begun to gain popular interest, although it remains somewhat at the fringe in U.S. media.<ref>Fisher, I. (1933) \"The Debt-Deflation Theory of Great Depressions,\" Econometrica 1 (4): 337-57</ref><ref>Grant, J. (2007) \"Learn From the Fall of Rome, U.S. Warned,\" Financial Times (14 August)</ref><ref>Robert Peston, [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-15820601 \"UK's debts 'biggest in the world',\"] BBC (21 November 2011).</ref><ref>{{Cite web |author=John T. Harvey |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/johntharvey/2012/07/18/why-you-should-love-government-deficits/ |title=Why You Should Love Government Deficits |publisher=Forbes |date=Jul 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Ben Bernanke (1983) ==\nThe lack of influence of Fisher's debt-deflation in academic economics is thus described by [[Ben Bernanke]] in {{Harvtxt|Bernanke|1995|loc=p. 17}}:\n:Fisher's idea was less influential in academic circles, though, because of the counterargument that debt-deflation represented no more than a redistribution from one group (debtors) to another (creditors). Absent implausibly large differences in marginal spending propensities among the groups, it was suggested, pure redistributions should have no significant macroeconomic effects.\n\nBuilding on both the monetary hypothesis of [[Milton Friedman]] and [[Anna Schwartz]] as well as the debt deflation hypothesis of Irving Fisher, Bernanke developed an alternative way in which the financial crisis affected output. He builds on Fisher's argument that dramatic declines in the price level and nominal incomes lead to increasing real debt burdens, which in turn leads to debtor insolvency, thus leading to lowered [[aggregate demand]] and further decline in the price level, which develops into a debt deflation spiral. According to Bernanke a small decline in the price level simply reallocates wealth from debtors to creditors without doing damage to the economy. But when the deflation is severe, falling asset prices along with debtor bankruptcies lead to a decline in the nominal value of assets on bank balance sheets. Banks will react by tightening their credit conditions. That in turn leads to a [[credit crunch]] that does serious harm to the economy. A credit crunch lowers investment and consumption, which leads to declining aggregate demand, which additionally contributes to the deflationary spiral.<ref>Randall E. Parker, ''Reflections on the Great Depression'', Edward Elgar Publishing, 2003, {{ISBN|9781843765509}}, p. 14-15</ref>\n\n== Post-Keynesian interpretation ==\nDebt deflation has been studied and developed largely in the [[Post-Keynesian economics|post-Keynesian school]].\n\nThe [[financial instability hypothesis]] of [[Hyman Minsky]], developed in the 1980s, complements Fisher's theory in providing an explanation of how credit bubbles form: the financial instability hypothesis explains how bubbles form, while debt deflation explains how they burst and the resulting economic effects. Mathematical models of debt deflation have recently been developed by post-Keynesian economist [[Steve Keen]].\n\n== Solutions ==\nFisher viewed the solution to debt deflation as [[reflation]] \u2013 returning the price level to the level it was prior to deflation \u2013 followed by price stability, which would break the \"vicious spiral\" of debt deflation. In the absence of reflation, he predicted an end only after \"needless and cruel bankruptcy, unemployment, and starvation\",<ref>Compare: \"Let us beware of this dangerous theory of [[economic equilibrium|equilibrium]] which is supposed to be automatically established. A certain kind of equilibrium, it is true, is reestablished in the long run, but it is after a frightful amount of suffering.\", [[Simonde de Sismondi]], ''New Principles of Political Economy,'' vol. 1 (1819), pp. 20\u201321.</ref> followed by \"a new boom-depression sequence\":<ref>[http://seekingalpha.com/article/104135-irving-fisher-on-debt-deflation-and-depression Irving Fisher on Debt, Deflation, and Depression], Brian Griffin, November 05, 2008, Seeking Alpha</ref>\n{{quote|Unless some counteracting cause comes along to prevent the fall in the price level, such a depression as that of 1929-33 (namely when the more the debtors pay the more they owe) tends to continue, going deeper, in a vicious spiral, for many years. There is then no tendency of the boat to stop tipping until it has capsized. Ultimately, of course, but only after almost universal bankruptcy, the indebtedness must cease to grow greater and begin to grow less. Then comes recovery and a tendency for a new boom-depression sequence. This is the so-called \"natural\" way out of a depression, via needless and cruel bankruptcy, unemployment, and starvation.\n\nOn the other hand, if the foregoing analysis is correct, it is always economically possible to stop or prevent such a depression simply by reflating the price level up to the average level at which outstanding debts were contracted by existing debtors and assumed by existing creditors, and then maintaining that level unchanged.}}\n\nLater commentators do not in general believe that reflation is sufficient, and primarily propose two solutions: [[debt relief]] \u2013 particularly via [[inflation]] \u2013 and [[fiscal stimulus]].\n\nFollowing Hyman Minsky, some argue that the debts assumed at the height of the bubble simply cannot be repaid \u2013 that they are based on the assumption of ''rising'' asset prices, rather than stable asset prices: the so-called \"Ponzi units\". Such debts cannot be repaid in a stable price environment, much less a deflationary environment, and instead must either be defaulted on, forgiven, or restructured.\n\nWidespread debt relief either requires government action or individual negotiations between every debtor and creditor, and is thus politically contentious or requires much labor. A categorical method of debt relief is inflation, which reduces the ''real'' debt burden, as debts are generally ''nominally'' denominated: if wages and prices double, but debts remain the same, the debt level drops in half. The effect of inflation is more pronounced the higher the [[debt to GDP ratio]] is: at a 50% ratio, one year of 10% inflation reduces the ratio by approximately <math>50\\% \\times 10\\% = 5\\%,</math> to 45%, while at a 300% ratio, one year of 10% inflation reduces the ratio by approximately <math>300\\% \\times 10\\% = 30\\%,</math> to 270%. In terms of [[Exchange rate|foreign exchange]], particularly of sovereign debt, inflation corresponds to [[currency devaluation]]. Inflation results in a wealth transfer from creditors to debtors, since creditors are not repaid as much in real terms as was expected, and on this basis this solution is criticized and politically contentious.\n\nIn the [[Keynesian economics|Keynesian]] tradition, some suggest that the fall in [[aggregate demand]] caused by falling ''private'' debt can be compensated for, at least temporarily, by growth in ''public'' debt \u2013 \"swap private debt for government debt\", or more evocatively, a government credit bubble replacing the private credit bubble. Indeed, some argue that this is the mechanism by which Keynesian economics actually works in a depression \u2013 \"[[fiscal stimulus]]\" simply meaning growth in government debt, hence boosting aggregate demand. Given the level of government debt growth required, some proponents of debt deflation such as [[Steve Keen]] are pessimistic about these Keynesian suggestions.<ref>[http://www.debtdeflation.com/blogs/2008/11/29/can-the-usa-debt-spend-its-way-out/ Can the USA debt-spend its way out?], November 29th, 2008, [[Steve Keen]]</ref>\n\nGiven the perceived political difficulties in debt relief and the suggested inefficacy of alternative courses of action, proponents of debt deflation are either pessimistic about solutions, expecting extended, possibly decades-long depressions, or believe that private debt relief (and related public debt relief \u2013 de facto sovereign debt repudiation) will result from an extended period of inflation.\n\n== Empirical support and modern mainstream interest ==\n[[File:U.S. Public and Private Debt as a % of GDP.jpg|thumb]]\nSeveral studies prove that the empirical support for the validity of the debt deflation hypothesis as laid down by Fisher and Bernanke is substantial, especially against the background of the Great Depression. Empirical support for the Bernanke transmission mechanism in the post\u2013World War II economic activity is weaker.<ref>Randall E. Parker, ''Reflections on the Great Depression'', Edward Elgar Publishing, 2003, {{ISBN|9781843765509}}, p. 15</ref>\n\nThere was a renewal of interest in debt deflation in academia in the 1980s and 1990s,<ref>{{Harv|Bernanke|1995|loc=p. 17}}</ref> and a further renewal of interest in debt deflation due to the [[financial crisis of 2007\u20132010]] and the ensuing [[Great Recession]].<ref name=\"shadow\" />\n\nIn 2008, Deepak Lal wrote, \"Bernanke has made sure that the second leg of a Fisherian debt deflation will not occur. But, past and present U.S. authorities have failed to adequately restore the balance sheets of over-leveraged banks, firms, and households.\"<ref>Deepak Lal, [http://www.cato.org/sites/cato.org/files/serials/files/cato-journal/2010/5/cj30n2-3.pdf \"The Great Crash of 2008: Causes and Consequences,\"] ''Cato Journal'', 30(2) (2010), p.271-72.</ref> After the [[Financial crisis of 2007\u20132008|financial crisis of 2007-2008]], [[Janet Yellen]] in her speech acknowledged Minsky's contribution to understanding how credit bubbles emerge, burst and lead to deflationary asset sales.<ref>https://www.frbsf.org/our-district/press/presidents-speeches/yellen-speeches/2009/april/yellen-minsky-meltdown-central-bankers/</ref> She described how a process of balance sheet deleveraging ensued while consumers cut back on their spending to be able to service their debt. Similarly invoking Minsky, in 2011 Charles J. Whalen wrote, \"the global economy has recently experienced a classic Minsky crisis - one with intertwined cyclical and institutional (structural) dimensions.\"<ref>Charles J. Whalen, [https://www.chapman.edu/law/_files/publications/CLR-15-charles-whalen.pdf \"Rethinking Economics for a New Era of Financial Regulation: The Political Economy of Hyman Minsky,\"] ''Chapman Law Review'', 15(1) (2011), p. 163.</ref>\n\n[[Kenneth Rogoff]] and [[Carmen Reinhart]]'s works published since 2009<ref>http://scholar.harvard.edu/rogoff/publications</ref> have addressed the causes of financial collapses both in recent modern times and throughout history, with a particular focus on the idea of [[debt overhang]]s.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Causes of the Great Depression#Debt deflation|Causes of the Great Depression: Debt deflation]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{citation | doi = 10.2307/2077848 | last = Bernanke | first = Ben | authorlink = Ben Bernanke | title = The Macroeconomics of the Great Depression: A Comparative Approach | journal = Journal of Money, Credit, and Banking | year = 1995 | volume = 27 | issue = 1 | pages = 1\u201328 | url = https://fraser.stlouisfed.org/title/1169/item/2399 | jstor = 2077848 }}\n* {{citation\n|first=Irving\n|last=Fisher\n|authorlink=Irving Fisher\n|url=https://fraser.stlouisfed.org/title/3596\n|title=The Debt-Deflation Theory of Great Depressions\n|journal=[[Econometrica]]\n|volume=1\n|issue=4\n|pages=337\u2013357\n|year=1933|doi=10.2307/1907327\n|jstor=1907327\n}}\n* {{Citation|last1=Eckstein|first1=Otto|authorlink1=Otto Eckstein|first2=Allen|last2=Sinai|title=The American Business Cycle: Continuity and Change|editor=Robert J. Gordon|publisher=University of Chicago Press|year=1990|chapter=1. The Mechanisms of the Business Cycle in the Postwar Period|isbn=978-0-226-30453-3|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/?id=P2f-icI-fM0C&pg=PA39|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/americanbusiness0000gord}}\n* {{citation | url = http://www.mckinsey.com/mgi/publications/debt_and_deleveraging/index.asp | title = Debt and deleveraging: The global credit bubble and its economic consequences |date=January 2010 | publisher = McKinsey Global Institute|author=Charles Roxburgh|author2=Susan Lund|author3=Tony Wimmer|author4=Eric Amar|author5=Charles Atkins|author6=Ju-Hon Kwek|author7=Richard Dobbs|author8=James Manyika }}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://debtdeflation.com DebtDeflation], by [[Steve Keen]]\n\n[[Category:Business cycle theories]]\n[[Category:Monetary economics]]\n", "text_old": "'''Debt deflation''' is a theory that [[recession]]s and [[depression (economics)|depressions]] are due to the overall level of debt rising in real value because of deflation, causing people to default on their consumer loans and mortgages. Bank assets fall because of the defaults and because the value of their collateral falls, leading to a surge in bank insolvencies, a reduction in lending and by extension, a reduction in spending.\n\nThe theory was developed by [[Irving Fisher]] following the [[Wall Street Crash of 1929]] and the ensuing [[Great Depression]]. The debt deflation theory was familiar to [[John Maynard Keynes]] prior to Fisher's discussion of it, but he found it lacking in comparison to what would become his theory of [[liquidity preference]].<ref>Pilkington, Philip (February 24, 2014). \"[http://fixingtheeconomists.wordpress.com/2014/02/24/keynes-liquidity-preference-trumps-debt-deflation-in-1931-and-2008/ Keynes' Liquidity Preference Trumps Debt Deflation in 1931 and 2008]\".</ref> The theory, however, has enjoyed a resurgence of interest since the 1980s, both in [[mainstream economics]] and in the [[heterodox economics|heterodox]] school of [[post-Keynesian economics]], and has subsequently been developed by such post-Keynesian economists as [[Hyman Minsky]]<ref>Minsky, Hyman (1992). \"The Financial Instability Hypothesis\".</ref> and by the mainstream economist [[Ben Bernanke]].<ref>Steve Keen (1995). \"Finance and economic breakdown: modelling Minsky\u2019s Financial Instability Hypothesis\", ''Journal of Post Keynesian Economics'', Vol. 17, No. 4, 607&ndash;635</ref>\n\n== Fisher's formulation (1933) ==\nIn Fisher's formulation of debt [[deflation]], when the debt bubble bursts the following sequence of events occurs:\n{{quote\n|Assuming, accordingly, that, at some point in time, a state of over-indebtedness exists, this will tend to lead to liquidation, through the alarm either of debtors or creditors or both. Then we may deduce the following chain of consequences in nine links:\n# Debt liquidation leads to distress selling and to\n# Contraction of deposit currency, as bank loans are paid off, and to a slowing down of velocity of circulation. This contraction of deposits and of their velocity, precipitated by distress selling, causes\n# A fall in the level of prices, in other words, a swelling of the dollar. Assuming, as above stated, that this fall of prices is not interfered with by reflation or otherwise, there must be\n# A still greater fall in the net worths of business, precipitating bankruptcies and\n# A like fall in profits, which in a \"capitalistic,\" that is, a private-profit society, leads the concerns which are running at a loss to make\n# A reduction in output, in trade and in employment of labor. These losses, bankruptcies and unemployment, lead to\n# pessimism and loss of confidence, which in turn lead to\n# Hoarding and slowing down still more the velocity of circulation.\n#:The above eight changes cause\n# Complicated disturbances in the rates of interest, in particular, a fall in the nominal, or money, rates and a rise in the real, or commodity, rates of interest.\n|{{Harv|Fisher|1933}}}}\n\n=== Rejection of previous assumptions ===\nPrior to his theory of debt deflation, Fisher had subscribed to the then-prevailing, and still mainstream, theory of [[general equilibrium]]. In order to apply this to financial markets, which involve transactions across time in the form of debt \u2013 receiving money now in exchange for something in future \u2013 he made two further assumptions:<ref name=\"dw42\">[http://www.debtdeflation.com/blogs/2010/01/24/debtwatch-no-42-the-economic-case-against-bernanke/ Debtwatch No. 42: The economic case against Bernanke], January 24th, 2010, [[Steve Keen]]</ref>\n:(A) The [[Market clearing|market must be cleared]]\u2014and cleared with respect to every interval of time.\n:(B) The debts must be paid. {{Harv|Fisher|1930|loc=p.495}}\nIn view of the Depression, he rejected equilibrium, and noted that in fact debts might not be paid, but instead defaulted on:\n{{quote|It is as absurd to assume that, for any long period of time, the variables in the economic organization, or any part of them, will \"stay put,\" in perfect equilibrium, as to assume that the Atlantic Ocean can ever be without a wave.|{{Harv|Fisher|1933|loc=p. 339}}}}\nHe further rejected the notion that over-confidence alone, rather than the resulting debt, was a significant factor in the Depression:\n{{quote|I fancy that over-confidence seldom does any great harm except when, as, and if, it beguiles its victims into debt. | {{Harv|Fisher|1933|loc=p. 339}}}}\nIn the context of this quote and the development of his theory and the central role it places on debt, it is of note that Fisher was personally ruined due to his having assumed debt due to his over-confidence prior to the crash, by buying stocks on margin.\n\nOther debt deflation theories do not assume that debts must be paid, noting the role that default, bankruptcy, and foreclosure play in modern economies.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://libertyloveandjusticeforall.com/2012/12/08/debt-reset-is-inevitable/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-12-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130603123926/http://libertyloveandjusticeforall.com/2012/12/08/debt-reset-is-inevitable/ |archive-date=2013-06-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== Initial mainstream interest ===\nInitially Fisher's work was largely ignored, in favor of the work of Keynes.<ref name=\"shadow\">[http://www.economist.com/businessfinance/displaystory.cfm?story_id=13104022 Out of Keynes's shadow], [[The Economist]], Feb 12th 2009</ref>\n\nThe following decades saw occasional mention of deflationary spirals due to debt in the mainstream, notably in ''[[The Great Crash, 1929]]'' of [[John Kenneth Galbraith]] in 1954, and the [[credit cycle]] has occasionally been cited as a leading cause of economic cycles in the post-WWII era, as in {{harv|Eckstein|Sinai|1990}}, but private debt remained absent from mainstream macroeconomic models.\n[[James Tobin]] cited Fisher as instrumental in his theory of economic instability.\n\nDebt-deflation theory has been studied since the 1930s but was largely ignored by neoclassical economists, and has only recently begun to gain popular interest, although it remains somewhat at the fringe in U.S. media.<ref>Fisher, I. (1933) \"The Debt-Deflation Theory of Great Depressions,\" Econometrica 1 (4): 337-57</ref><ref>Grant, J. (2007) \"Learn From the Fall of Rome, U.S. Warned,\" Financial Times (14 August)</ref><ref>Robert Peston, [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-15820601 \"UK's debts 'biggest in the world',\"] BBC (21 November 2011).</ref><ref>{{Cite web |author=John T. Harvey |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/johntharvey/2012/07/18/why-you-should-love-government-deficits/ |title=Why You Should Love Government Deficits |publisher=Forbes |date=Jul 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Ben Bernanke (1983) ==\nThe lack of influence of Fisher's debt-deflation in academic economics is thus described by [[Ben Bernanke]] in {{Harvtxt|Bernanke|1995|loc=p. 17}}:\n:Fisher's idea was less influential in academic circles, though, because of the counterargument that debt-deflation represented no more than a redistribution from one group (debtors) to another (creditors). Absent implausibly large differences in marginal spending propensities among the groups, it was suggested, pure redistributions should have no significant macroeconomic effects.\n\nBuilding on both the monetary hypothesis of [[Milton Friedman]] and [[Anna Schwartz]] as well as the debt deflation hypothesis of Irving Fisher, Bernanke developed an alternative way in which the financial crisis affected output. He builds on Fisher's argument that dramatic declines in the price level and nominal incomes lead to increasing real debt burdens, which in turn leads to debtor insolvency, thus leading to lowered [[aggregate demand]] and further decline in the price level, which develops into a debt deflation spiral. According to Bernanke a small decline in the price level simply reallocates wealth from debtors to creditors without doing damage to the economy. But when the deflation is severe, falling asset prices along with debtor bankruptcies lead to a decline in the nominal value of assets on bank balance sheets. Banks will react by tightening their credit conditions. That in turn leads to a [[credit crunch]] that does serious harm to the economy. A credit crunch lowers investment and consumption, which leads to declining aggregate demand, which additionally contributes to the deflationary spiral.<ref>Randall E. Parker, ''Reflections on the Great Depression'', Edward Elgar Publishing, 2003, {{ISBN|9781843765509}}, p. 14-15</ref>\n\n== Post-Keynesian interpretation ==\nDebt deflation has been studied and developed largely in the [[Post-Keynesian economics|post-Keynesian school]].\n\nThe [[financial instability hypothesis]] of [[Hyman Minsky]], developed in the 1980s, complements Fisher's theory in providing an explanation of how credit bubbles form: the financial instability hypothesis explains how bubbles form, while debt deflation explains how they burst and the resulting economic effects. Mathematical models of debt deflation have recently been developed by post-Keynesian economist [[Steve Keen]].\n\n== Solutions ==\nFisher viewed the solution to debt deflation as [[reflation]] \u2013 returning the price level to the level it was prior to deflation \u2013 followed by price stability, which would break the \"vicious spiral\" of debt deflation. In the absence of reflation, he predicted an end only after \"needless and cruel bankruptcy, unemployment, and starvation\",<ref>Compare: \"Let us beware of this dangerous theory of [[economic equilibrium|equilibrium]] which is supposed to be automatically established. A certain kind of equilibrium, it is true, is reestablished in the long run, but it is after a frightful amount of suffering.\", [[Simonde de Sismondi]], ''New Principles of Political Economy,'' vol. 1 (1819), pp. 20\u201321.</ref> followed by \"a new boom-depression sequence\":<ref>[http://seekingalpha.com/article/104135-irving-fisher-on-debt-deflation-and-depression Irving Fisher on Debt, Deflation, and Depression], Brian Griffin, November 05, 2008, Seeking Alpha</ref>\n{{quote|Unless some counteracting cause comes along to prevent the fall in the price level, such a depression as that of 1929-33 (namely when the more the debtors pay the more they owe) tends to continue, going deeper, in a vicious spiral, for many years. There is then no tendency of the boat to stop tipping until it has capsized. Ultimately, of course, but only after almost universal bankruptcy, the indebtedness must cease to grow greater and begin to grow less. Then comes recovery and a tendency for a new boom-depression sequence. This is the so-called \"natural\" way out of a depression, via needless and cruel bankruptcy, unemployment, and starvation.\n\nOn the other hand, if the foregoing analysis is correct, it is always economically possible to stop or prevent such a depression simply by reflating the price level up to the average level at which outstanding debts were contracted by existing debtors and assumed by existing creditors, and then maintaining that level unchanged.}}\n\nLater commentators do not in general believe that reflation is sufficient, and primarily propose two solutions: [[debt relief]] \u2013 particularly via [[inflation]] \u2013 and [[fiscal stimulus]].\n\nFollowing Hyman Minsky, some argue that the debts assumed at the height of the bubble simply cannot be repaid \u2013 that they are based on the assumption of ''rising'' asset prices, rather than stable asset prices: the so-called \"Ponzi units\". Such debts cannot be repaid in a stable price environment, much less a deflationary environment, and instead must either be defaulted on, forgiven, or restructured.\n\nWidespread debt relief either requires government action or individual negotiations between every debtor and creditor, and is thus politically contentious or requires much labor. A categorical method of debt relief is inflation, which reduces the ''real'' debt burden, as debts are generally ''nominally'' denominated: if wages and prices double, but debts remain the same, the debt level drops in half. The effect of inflation is more pronounced the higher the [[debt to GDP ratio]] is: at a 50% ratio, one year of 10% inflation reduces the ratio by approximately <math>50\\% \\times 10\\% = 5\\%,</math> to 45%, while at a 300% ratio, one year of 10% inflation reduces the ratio by approximately <math>300\\% \\times 10\\% = 30\\%,</math> to 270%. In terms of [[Exchange rate|foreign exchange]], particularly of sovereign debt, inflation corresponds to [[currency devaluation]]. Inflation results in a wealth transfer from creditors to debtors, since creditors are not repaid as much in real terms as was expected, and on this basis this solution is criticized and politically contentious.\n\nIn the [[Keynesian economics|Keynesian]] tradition, some suggest that the fall in [[aggregate demand]] caused by falling ''private'' debt can be compensated for, at least temporarily, by growth in ''public'' debt \u2013 \"swap private debt for government debt\", or more evocatively, a government credit bubble replacing the private credit bubble. Indeed, some argue that this is the mechanism by which Keynesian economics actually works in a depression \u2013 \"[[fiscal stimulus]]\" simply meaning growth in government debt, hence boosting aggregate demand. Given the level of government debt growth required, some proponents of debt deflation such as [[Steve Keen]] are pessimistic about these Keynesian suggestions.<ref>[http://www.debtdeflation.com/blogs/2008/11/29/can-the-usa-debt-spend-its-way-out/ Can the USA debt-spend its way out?], November 29th, 2008, [[Steve Keen]]</ref>\n\nGiven the perceived political difficulties in debt relief and the suggested inefficacy of alternative courses of action, proponents of debt deflation are either pessimistic about solutions, expecting extended, possibly decades-long depressions, or believe that private debt relief (and related public debt relief \u2013 de facto sovereign debt repudiation) will result from an extended period of inflation.\n\n== Empirical support and modern mainstream interest ==\n[[File:U.S. Public and Private Debt as a % of GDP.jpg|thumb]]\nSeveral studies prove that the empirical support for the validity of the debt deflation hypothesis as laid down by Fisher and Bernanke is substantial, especially against the background of the Great Depression. Empirical support for the Bernanke transmission mechanism in the post\u2013World War II economic activity is weaker.<ref>Randall E. Parker, ''Reflections on the Great Depression'', Edward Elgar Publishing, 2003, {{ISBN|9781843765509}}, p. 15</ref>\n\nThere was a renewal of interest in debt deflation in academia in the 1980s and 1990s,<ref>{{Harv|Bernanke|1995|loc=p. 17}}</ref> and a further renewal of interest in debt deflation due to the [[financial crisis of 2007\u20132010]] and the ensuing [[Great Recession]].<ref name=\"shadow\" />\n\nIn 2008, Deepak Lal wrote, \"Bernanke has made sure that the second leg of a Fisherian debt deflation will not occur. But, past and present U.S. authorities have failed to adequately restore the balance sheets of over-leveraged banks, firms, and households.\"<ref>Deepak Lal, [http://www.cato.org/sites/cato.org/files/serials/files/cato-journal/2010/5/cj30n2-3.pdf \"The Great Crash of 2008: Causes and Consequences,\"] ''Cato Journal'', 30(2) (2010), p.271-72.</ref> After the [[Financial crisis of 2007\u20132008|financial crisis of 2007-2008]], [[Janet Yellen]] in her speech acknowledged Minsky's contribution to understanding how credit bubbles emerge, burst and lead to deflationary asset sales.<ref>https://www.frbsf.org/our-district/press/presidents-speeches/yellen-speeches/2009/april/yellen-minsky-meltdown-central-bankers/</ref> She described how a process of balance sheet deleveraging ensued while consumers cut back on their spending to be able to service their debt. Similarly invoking Minsky, in 2011 Charles J. Whalen wrote, \"the global economy has recently experienced a classic Minsky crisis - one with intertwined cyclical and institutional (structural) dimensions.\"<ref>Charles J. Whalen, [https://www.chapman.edu/law/_files/publications/CLR-15-charles-whalen.pdf \"Rethinking Economics for a New Era of Financial Regulation: The Political Economy of Hyman Minsky,\"] ''Chapman Law Review'', 15(1) (2011), p. 163.</ref>\n\n[[Kenneth Rogoff]] and [[Carmen Reinhart]]'s works published since 2009<ref>http://scholar.harvard.edu/rogoff/publications</ref> have addressed the causes of financial collapses both in recent modern times and throughout history, with a particular focus on the idea of [[debt overhang]]s.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Causes of the Great Depression#Debt deflation|Causes of the Great Depression: Debt deflation]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{citation | doi = 10.2307/2077848 | last = Bernanke | first = Ben | authorlink = Ben Bernanke | title = The Macroeconomics of the Great Depression: A Comparative Approach | journal = Journal of Money, Credit, and Banking | year = 1995 | volume = 27 | issue = 1 | pages = 1\u201328 | url = https://fraser.stlouisfed.org/title/1169/item/2399 | jstor = 2077848 }}\n* {{citation\n|first=Irving\n|last=Fisher\n|authorlink=Irving Fisher\n|url=https://fraser.stlouisfed.org/title/3596\n|title=The Debt-Deflation Theory of Great Depressions\n|journal=[[Econometrica]]\n|volume=1\n|issue=4\n|pages=337\u2013357\n|year=1933|doi=10.2307/1907327\n|jstor=1907327\n}}\n* {{Citation|last1=Eckstein|first1=Otto|authorlink1=Otto Eckstein|first2=Allen|last2=Sinai|title=The American Business Cycle: Continuity and Change|editor=Robert J. Gordon|publisher=University of Chicago Press|year=1990|chapter=1. The Mechanisms of the Business Cycle in the Postwar Period|isbn=978-0-226-30453-3|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/?id=P2f-icI-fM0C&pg=PA39|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/americanbusiness0000gord}}\n* {{citation | url = http://www.mckinsey.com/mgi/publications/debt_and_deleveraging/index.asp | title = Debt and deleveraging: The global credit bubble and its economic consequences |date=January 2010 | publisher = McKinsey Global Institute|author=Charles Roxburgh|author2=Susan Lund|author3=Tony Wimmer|author4=Eric Amar|author5=Charles Atkins|author6=Ju-Hon Kwek|author7=Richard Dobbs|author8=James Manyika }}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://debtdeflation.com DebtDeflation], by [[Steve Keen]]\n\n[[Category:Business cycle theories]]\n[[Category:Monetary economics]]\n", "name_user": "H2NCH2COOH", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInitial mainstream interest", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Debt_deflation"}
{"title_page": "Jiri Lev", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Jiri Lev\n| image              = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = \n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| residence          = \n| nationality        = [[Australia]], [[Czechia]]\n| caption            = \n| other_names        = \n| education          = [[Master of Architecture]]\n| alma_mater         = [[University of Newcastle (Australia)]]\n| occupation         = Building and urban designer\n| years_active       = 1998\u2013present\n| organization       = [[Australian Institute of Architects]]\n| known_for          = Advocacy of and education in sustainable and resilient architecture and urban design\n| notable_works      = \n| home_town          = [[Prague]]\n| website            = \n}}\n\n'''Jiri Lev''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|j|\u026a|r|\u026a|_|\u02c8|l|\u025b|v}}, {{lang-cs|Ji\u0159\u00ed Lev}}) is an Australian building and urban designer, working in the field of [[Sustainable architecture|sustainable]] public, residential and disaster-relief architecture.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.australiandesignreview.com/architecture/architects-assist-offers-pro-bono-design-services-to-aussies-impacted-by-bushfire-crisis/|title=Architects Assist offers pro-bono bushfire services|last=|first=|date=2020-01-08|website=Australian Design Review|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nLev's works are known for their highly varied, locally appropriate architectural style, rigorous application of sustainable design principles and prolific use of natural, near-raw and locally sourced construction materials, such as [[timber]], stone, [[hempcrete]], [[canite]] or clay and lime products<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=http://mpavilion.org/collaborator/jiri-lev/|title=Jiri Lev|last=|first=|date=|website=MPavilion|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> ([[Gulgong Holtermann Museum]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mudgeeguardian.com.au/story/2839026/gulgongs-holtermann-museum-launch-reveals-first-drawings/|title=Gulgong's Holtermann Museum launch reveals first drawings|last=WATSON|first=ELLE|date=2015-01-26|website=Mudgee Guardian|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, Courtyard House<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=December 2019 - February 2020|title=The Courtyard House|url=|journal=The Owner Builder|volume=216|pages=42-43|via=}}</ref>).\n\nHe teaches sustainable and resilient architecture in lectures, workshops and writing. Promoting regionally specific architectural design, he often refers to [[vernacular architecture]] and the principles of [[New Urbanism|new urbanism]], rejecting globalised design trends as destructive to [[genius loci]].<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archipro.co.nz/articles/architecture/a-changing-climate-architecture-in-2020-and-beyond-archipro|title=A changing climate: architecture in 2020 and beyond|last=Chapman|first=Clare|date=21 January 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\n== Biography ==\nLev was born in [[Czech Republic|Czechia]] (then part of [[Czechoslovakia]])<ref name=\":4\" /> to parents Jiri Loew, Czech architect, academic and politician<ref>{{Cite book|last=Michal|first=Igor|title=Krajinn\u00fd r\u00e1z|last2=Loew|first2=Jiri|publisher=Lesnicka prace|year=2003|isbn=80-86386-27-9|location=|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Kope\u010dek|first=Pavel|title=Projevy k\u0159es\u0165ansk\u00e9 liturgie v kulturn\u00ed krajin\u011b|last2=Loew|first2=Jiri|last3=Kucera|first3=Petr|publisher=[[Mendel University]]|year=2015|isbn=978-80-7509-387-5|location=|pages=}}</ref> and Lydie Loewova, architect. Prior to the [[Velvet Revolution]] the family was persecuted by the communist regime.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|last1=W|first1=Dan|url=https://hivelife.com/architects-assist/|title=The Australian Architects Offering Pro-Bono Design Services to Bushfire Survivors|date=4 March 2020|work=Hive Life: The people, places and ideas shaping Asia Pacific|access-date=|url-status=live|publisher=The Hive Worldwide}}</ref>\n\nHe first established his multidisciplinary design practice in [[Prague]] in 1998.<ref name=\":5\" /> In 2005 he moved to [[Australia]], where he studied [[architecture]] at the [[University of Newcastle (Australia)|University of Newcastle]] under [[Richard Leplastrier]] and [[Kerry and Lindsay Clare]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn 2014 Lev founded [[ArchiCamp]],<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://architectureau.com/articles/architecture-in-the-field-archicamp-2015/|title=Architecture in the field: Archicamp 2015|last=|first=|date=|website=ArchitectureAU|language=en-AU|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-10-19/architecture-students-helping-dungog-through-flood-recovery/6865140|title=University students design infrastructure for flood-ravaged Dungog|last=Virtue|first=Robert|date=2015-10-19|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> an irregular grassroots gathering of accomplished architects and architecture students, introducing the concept of loosely organised, guerilla style events, focused on learning and invited architectural intervention within disadvantaged or disaster-stricken rural communities.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mudgeeguardian.com.au/story/3414880/architects-and-designers-plan-projects-for-flood-affected-town/|title=Architects and designers plan projects for flood affected town|last=WATSON|first=ELLE|date=2015-10-12|website=Mudgee Guardian|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.portstephensexaminer.com.au/story/3435713/students-shepherd-ideas/|title=Students shepherd ideas|last=WATTS|first=ELLIE-MARIE|date=2015-10-22|website=Port Stephens Examiner|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.maitlandmercury.com.au/story/3402847/sustainable-architecture-gathering-comes-to-shepherds-ground-photos/|title=Sustainable architecture gathering comes to Shepherds Ground {{!}} PHOTOS|last=SWAIN|first=EMMA|date=2015-10-05|website=The Maitland Mercury|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the [[2019\u201320 Australian bushfire season|2019-20 Australian bushfires]] Lev established [[Architects Assist]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dezeen.com/2020/01/07/australian-architects-assist-bushfire-crisis-news/|title=Australian architects offer free design services to bushfire victims|last=|first=|date=2020-01-07|website=Dezeen|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archpaper.com/2020/01/architects-organize-pro-bono-design-services-australian-bushfires/|title=Architects organize to provide pro-bono services to those affected by Australian bushfires|last=|first=|date=2020-01-08|website=Archpaper.com|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vogue.com.au/vogue-living/design/architects-are-offering-free-services-to-bushfire-victims-whove-lost-their-homes/news-story/4dde49ee12d9ef3b53385caa5689e332|title=Architects and interior designers are offering free services to bushfire victims who\u2019ve lost their homes|last=Whish|first=Bec|date=2020-01-16|website=Vogue Australia|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> a professional organisation of architects and architecture students providing pro bono assistance to the community, serving as a \"platform for equitable access to sustainable and resilient architecture.\" By February 2020 the organisation represented over two thousand members.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.architectureanddesign.com.au/news/architect-s-assist-in-rebuilding-australia|title=Architect\u2019s Assist in rebuilding Australian bushfire ravaged homes|last=|first=|date=8 January 2020|website=Architecture & Design|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://architectureau.com/articles/can-architects-help-bushfire-ravaged-communities-rebuild/|title=Can architects help bushfire-ravaged communities rebuild?|last=|first=|date=7 January 2020|website=ArchitectureAU|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2020 Lev revealed his plans for a new model settlement in [[Tasmania]] addressing the housing and environmental crises. The development proposal was loosely inspired by the [[cohousing]] and [[ecovillage]] movement as well as traditional European settlements.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Compton|first=Leon|url=|title=Intentional Communities|date=18 February 2020|work=ABC Radio Hobart|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lev, Jiri}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Australian architects]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Czech descent]]\n[[Category:Brno University of Technology alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Jiri Lev\n| image              = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = \n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| residence          = \n| nationality        = [[Australia]], [[Czechia]]\n| caption            = \n| other_names        = \n| education          = [[Master of Architecture]]\n| alma_mater         = [[University of Newcastle (Australia)]]\n| occupation         = Building and urban designer\n| years_active       = 1998\u2013present\n| organization       = [[Australian Institute of Architects]]\n| known_for          = Advocacy of and education in sustainable and resilient architecture and urban design\n| notable_works      = \n| home_town          = [[Prague]]\n| website            = \n}}\n\n'''Jiri Lev''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|j|\u026a|r|\u026a|_|\u02c8|l|\u025b|v}}, {{lang-cs|Ji\u0159\u00ed Lev}}) is an Australian building and urban designer, working in the field of [[Sustainable architecture|sustainable]] public, residential and disaster-relief architecture.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.australiandesignreview.com/architecture/architects-assist-offers-pro-bono-design-services-to-aussies-impacted-by-bushfire-crisis/|title=Architects Assist offers pro-bono bushfire services|last=|first=|date=2020-01-08|website=Australian Design Review|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nLev's works are known for their highly varied, locally appropriate architectural style, rigorous application of sustainable design principles and prolific use of natural, near-raw and locally sourced construction materials, such as [[timber]], stone, [[hempcrete]], [[canite]] or clay and lime products ([[Gulgong Holtermann Museum]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mudgeeguardian.com.au/story/2839026/gulgongs-holtermann-museum-launch-reveals-first-drawings/|title=Gulgong's Holtermann Museum launch reveals first drawings|last=WATSON|first=ELLE|date=2015-01-26|website=Mudgee Guardian|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, Courtyard House<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=December 2019 - February 2020|title=The Courtyard House|url=|journal=The Owner Builder|volume=216|pages=42-43|via=}}</ref>).<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nLev is an advocate of sustainable and resilient architecture, promoting local [[vernacular architecture]] and the principles of [[New Urbanism|new urbanism]]. He is often critical of contemporary architecture, having referred to some of it as \"expensive paper boxes\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archipro.co.nz/articles/architecture/a-changing-climate-architecture-in-2020-and-beyond-archipro|title=A changing climate: architecture in 2020 and beyond|last=Chapman|first=Clare|date=21 January 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \"destructive to [[genius loci]].\"<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=http://mpavilion.org/collaborator/jiri-lev/|title=Jiri Lev|last=|first=|date=|website=MPavilion|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He teaches sustainable and resilient architecture in lectures, workshops and writing.\n\n== Biography ==\nLev was born in [[Czech Republic|Czechia]] (then part of [[Czechoslovakia]])<ref name=\":4\" /> to parents Jiri Loew, Czech architect, academic and politician<ref>{{Cite book|last=Michal|first=Igor|title=Krajinn\u00fd r\u00e1z|last2=Loew|first2=Jiri|publisher=Lesnicka prace|year=2003|isbn=80-86386-27-9|location=|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Kope\u010dek|first=Pavel|title=Projevy k\u0159es\u0165ansk\u00e9 liturgie v kulturn\u00ed krajin\u011b|last2=Loew|first2=Jiri|last3=Kucera|first3=Petr|publisher=[[Mendel University]]|year=2015|isbn=978-80-7509-387-5|location=|pages=}}</ref> and Lydie Loewova, architect. Prior to the [[Velvet Revolution]] the family was persecuted by the communist regime.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|last1=W|first1=Dan|url=https://hivelife.com/architects-assist/|title=The Australian Architects Offering Pro-Bono Design Services to Bushfire Survivors|date=4 March 2020|work=Hive Life: The people, places and ideas shaping Asia Pacific|access-date=|url-status=live|publisher=The Hive Worldwide}}</ref>\n\nHe first established his multidisciplinary design practice in [[Prague]] in 1998.<ref name=\":5\" /> In 2005 he moved to [[Australia]], where he studied [[architecture]] at the [[University of Newcastle (Australia)|University of Newcastle]] under [[Richard Leplastrier]] and [[Kerry and Lindsay Clare]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn 2014 Lev founded [[ArchiCamp]],<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://architectureau.com/articles/architecture-in-the-field-archicamp-2015/|title=Architecture in the field: Archicamp 2015|last=|first=|date=|website=ArchitectureAU|language=en-AU|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-10-19/architecture-students-helping-dungog-through-flood-recovery/6865140|title=University students design infrastructure for flood-ravaged Dungog|last=Virtue|first=Robert|date=2015-10-19|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> an irregular grassroots gathering of accomplished architects and architecture students, introducing the concept of loosely organised, guerilla style events, focused on learning and invited architectural intervention within disadvantaged or disaster-stricken rural communities.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mudgeeguardian.com.au/story/3414880/architects-and-designers-plan-projects-for-flood-affected-town/|title=Architects and designers plan projects for flood affected town|last=WATSON|first=ELLE|date=2015-10-12|website=Mudgee Guardian|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.portstephensexaminer.com.au/story/3435713/students-shepherd-ideas/|title=Students shepherd ideas|last=WATTS|first=ELLIE-MARIE|date=2015-10-22|website=Port Stephens Examiner|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.maitlandmercury.com.au/story/3402847/sustainable-architecture-gathering-comes-to-shepherds-ground-photos/|title=Sustainable architecture gathering comes to Shepherds Ground {{!}} PHOTOS|last=SWAIN|first=EMMA|date=2015-10-05|website=The Maitland Mercury|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the [[2019\u201320 Australian bushfire season|2019-20 Australian bushfires]] Lev established [[Architects Assist]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dezeen.com/2020/01/07/australian-architects-assist-bushfire-crisis-news/|title=Australian architects offer free design services to bushfire victims|last=|first=|date=2020-01-07|website=Dezeen|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archpaper.com/2020/01/architects-organize-pro-bono-design-services-australian-bushfires/|title=Architects organize to provide pro-bono services to those affected by Australian bushfires|last=|first=|date=2020-01-08|website=Archpaper.com|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vogue.com.au/vogue-living/design/architects-are-offering-free-services-to-bushfire-victims-whove-lost-their-homes/news-story/4dde49ee12d9ef3b53385caa5689e332|title=Architects and interior designers are offering free services to bushfire victims who\u2019ve lost their homes|last=Whish|first=Bec|date=2020-01-16|website=Vogue Australia|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> a professional organisation of architects and architecture students providing pro bono assistance to the community, serving as a \"platform for equitable access to sustainable and resilient architecture.\" By February 2020 the organisation represented over two thousand members.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.architectureanddesign.com.au/news/architect-s-assist-in-rebuilding-australia|title=Architect\u2019s Assist in rebuilding Australian bushfire ravaged homes|last=|first=|date=8 January 2020|website=Architecture & Design|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://architectureau.com/articles/can-architects-help-bushfire-ravaged-communities-rebuild/|title=Can architects help bushfire-ravaged communities rebuild?|last=|first=|date=7 January 2020|website=ArchitectureAU|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2020 Lev revealed his plans for a new model settlement in [[Tasmania]] addressing the housing and environmental crises. The development proposal was loosely inspired by the [[cohousing]] and [[ecovillage]] movement as well as traditional European settlements.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Compton|first=Leon|url=|title=Intentional Communities|date=18 February 2020|work=ABC Radio Hobart|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lev, Jiri}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Australian architects]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Czech descent]]\n[[Category:Brno University of Technology alumni]]\n", "name_user": "SergeevnaA", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jiri_Lev"}
{"title_page": "CL (singer)", "text_new": "{{Korean name|Lee}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = CL\n| image              = CL of 2NE1 2013 (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = CL in 2013\n| native_name        = \uc774\ucc44\ub9b0\n| native_name_lang   = ko\n| birth_name         = Lee Chae-rin\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1991|02|26}}\n| birth_place        = [[Seoul]], South Korea\n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) -->\n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = South Korean\n| other_names        =\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Singer-songwriter|rapper}}\n| years_active       = 2007\u2013present\n| known_for          = \n| notable_works      = \n| awards             = \n| website            = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background       = solo_singer\n| alias            = \n| origin           = [[Seoul]], South Korea\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[K-pop]]|[[Hip hop music|hip-hop]]|[[reggae fusion]]|[[Trap music (EDM)|trap]]}}\n| instrument       = Vocals\n| label            = {{hlist|[[YG Entertainment|YG]]|[[School Boy Records|School Boy]]|SuneV}}\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[2NE1]]|[[YG Family]]}}\n}}\n| module2            = {{Infobox Korean name|child=yes\n | title   = [[Korean name]]\n | hangul  = {{linktext|\uc774|\ucc44|\ub9b0}}\n | hanja   = {{linktext|\u674e|\u5f69|\u9e9f}}\n | rr      = I Chae-rin\n | mr      = I Ch'ae-rin\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Lee Chae-rin'''  (born on February 26, 1991<ref name=\"Russell2014\">{{cite book|author=Mark Russell|title=K-Pop Now!: The Korean Music Revolution|page=77|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=etDZAwAAQBAJ|date=29 April 2014|publisher=Tuttle Publishing|isbn=978-1-4629-1411-1}}</ref>), better known by her stage name '''CL''', is a South Korean singer-songwriter, rapper and record producer.<ref name=\"Basic\">{{cite web |url=http://music.naver.com/artist/home.nhn?artistId=117570 |title=CL at Naver Music |language=Korean |work=Naver Music |publisher=NHN Corp |accessdate=November 13, 2010}}</ref> Born in [[Seoul]], South Korea, she spent much of her early life in Japan and France.<ref name=\"CL interview\">{{cite web |url=http://spn.edaily.co.kr/entertain/newsRead.asp?newsid=01230006589691544 |title=CL, \"\ub370\ubaa8 \ud14c\uc774\ud504 \ub4e4\uace0 \ubb34\uc791\uc815 YG \ubb38 \ub178\ud06c\" |trans-title=CL, \"knocked on the YG Entertainment door to hand in my demo tape\" |language=Korean |author=Park, Mi-ae |date=May 22, 2009 |accessdate=November 23, 2010 |work=eDaily SPN |publisher=eDaily }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> CL trained at [[JYP Entertainment]] before joining [[YG Entertainment]] at the age of fifteen and debuted as a member of the girl group [[2NE1]] in 2009.<ref name=\"debut with 3 members\">{{cite web |url=http://world.kbs.co.kr/english/entertainment/enter_chart_detail.htm?No=9375 |title=Female Big Bang to be Unveiled |date=March 25, 2009 |accessdate=November 13, 2010 |work=KBS Global}}</ref> Following her group taking a break, CL embarked her solo career in the United States in 2015. In 2016, 2NE1 officially disbanded and she remained a solo act under YG until her contract expired in November 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8543125/cl-leaves-k-pop-label-yg-entertainment |title=CL Leaves Longtime K-Pop Label: Report |accessdate=December 10, 2019 |work=billboard.com}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n===1991\u20132008: Early life and career beginnings===\nLee Chae-rin was born in [[Seoul]], South Korea, but spent most of her childhood living in [[Paris]], [[Tsukuba, Ibaraki|Tsukuba]], and [[Tokyo]]. When she was 13, she moved to Paris alone where she studied for two years.<ref name=\"naver.com\"/> Lee got an audition with YG Entertainment when she was 15.<ref name=\"CL interview\"/><ref name=\"naver.com\">{{cite web |url=http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=106&oid=420&aid=0000000361|title=[CL] 1\ubd80. \uc0c8\ud574 \uccab \ub0a0, \ub208\ubb3c \uc816\uc740 \uc790\uc7a5\uba74 \ub4dc\uc154\ubcf4\uc168\ub098\uc694? | language = Korean | work=OSEN |accessdate=June 13, 2013}}</ref> Her first feature on a song recording was [[Big Bang (South Korean band)|Big Bang]]'s \"Intro (Hot Issue)\" in 2007. Later that year, Lee performed for the first time on stage at [[Seoul Broadcasting System]]'s Gayo Daejeon alongside her label mates.{{citation needed|date=November 2010}} Her first credited appearance in a song was in 2008, with [[Uhm Jung-hwa]]'s \"DJ,\" in which she rapped.<ref name=\"Uhm Jung Hwa\">{{cite web |url=http://www.yesasia.com/global/uhm-jung-hwa-2008-mini-album-d-i-s-c-o/1011125524-0-0-0-en/info.html |title=Uhm Jung Hwa 2008 Mini Album \u2013 D.I.S.C.O |accessdate=November 13, 2010 |work=YesAsia.com}}</ref>\n\nFakunle Omodolapo Deborah wrote all of Lee Chaerin's songs amd most of her accessories are bought with Deborah's money===2009\u20132013: Debut with 2NE1 and solo career beginnings===\n{{main|2NE1}}\nLee took on the stage name 'CL' and was placed as the leader and main rapper of 2NE1, alongside [[Park Bom|Bom]], [[Sandara Park]] and [[Minzy]]. The group then collaborated with label-mates Big Bang for the song \"[[Lollipop (Big Bang and 2NE1 song)|Lollipop]]\" before officially debuting on [[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS]]'s ''[[The Music Trend]]'' on May 17, 2009 where they performed \"[[Fire (2NE1 song)|Fire]]\". 2NE1 achieved significant success with the number-one single \"I Don't Care\" from their first extended play, ''[[2NE1 (2009 EP)|2NE1]]'', which won them the \"Song of the Year\" award at the 2009 [[Mnet Asian Music Awards]], making them the first rookie group to win a daesang in the same year of debut.\n\nIn August 2009, she collaborated with label-mates [[G-Dragon]] and [[Teddy Park]] of [[1TYM]] for the single \"The Leaders\", featured on G-Dragon's first solo album, ''[[Heartbreaker (G-Dragon song)|Heartbreaker]]''. The same month, after the group finished with \"I Don't Care\" promotions, CL collaborated with fellow member Minzy for \"Please Don't Go,\" which charted at number six on the [[Gaon Chart]] by the end of November.<ref name=\"Gaon\">{{cite web |url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/search/list.gaon?Search_str=CL&x=23&y=20 |title=Gaon Chart Search: CL |language=Korean |accessdate=November 13, 2010 |work=Gaon Chart |publisher=Korea Music Content Industry Association}}</ref> Her first solo single, \"[[The Baddest Female]]\", was released on 28 May 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allkpop.com/article/2013/05/the-baddest-female-cl-releases-her-solo-debut-mv | title=The Baddest Female CL releases her solo debut MV | publisher=allkpop | date=2013-05-28}}</ref> For 2NE1's second album ''[[Crush (2NE1 album)|Crush]]'', CL wrote the lyrics and co-composed the music for the tracks \"Crush\", \"If I Were You\", and \"Baby I Miss You\". She also wrote the lyrics for her solo track \"MTBD\", as well as the track \"Scream\".<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/6281868/cl-solo-america-scooter-braun-2ne1 \"K-Pop Superstar CL to Enter America With Scooter Braun\"], ''Billboard'', 16 October 2014. Accessed 13 October 2015.</ref>\n\n===2014\u20132019: Stand-alone singles and featured appearances===\n[[File:CL at Twin Towers Alive Event Malaysia.jpg|thumb|200px|CL in 2013]]\nIn October 2014, it was announced that CL was planning to debut as a solo artist the following year in the United States, teaming up with [[Scooter Braun]] as her manager.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allkpop.com/article/2014/10/2ne1s-cl-confirmed-to-make-her-us-debut-as-a-solo-artist|title=2NE1's CL confirmed to make her U.S. debut as a solo artist}}</ref> In May 2015, she featured in [[Diplo]]'s single \"[[Doctor Pepper (song)|Doctor Pepper]]\", alongside [[Riff Raff (rapper)|Riff Raff]] and [[OG Maco]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hypebeast.com/2015/8/diplo-featuring-cl-riff-raff-og-maco-doctor-pepper-music-video|title=Diplo Featuring CL, RiFF RAFF & OG Maco \"Doctor Pepper\" Music Video}}</ref> In November 2015, CL released her first single \"[[Hello Bitches]]\", as a teaser for her upcoming EP ''Lifted''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fuse.tv/2015/09/cl-lifted-english-ep|title=CL Preps Debut English EP 'Lifted' for Fall|access-date=2016-08-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/6670465/diplo-cl-birthday-one-kpop|title=Diplo Talks K-Pop & New Songs Recorded With CL in 'Time' Interview|access-date=2016-08-18}}</ref> The lead single, \"[[Lifted (CL song)|Lifted]]\" was released on August 19, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.allkpop.com/article/2016/08/cl-gets-lifted-in-her-newest-solo-mv|title=CL gets 'Lifted' in her newest solo MV! {{!}} allkpop.com|access-date=2016-08-18}}</ref> The song appeared in the Top 30 of iTunes\u2019 Hip-Hop/Rap chart within three hours of being released, peaking at 21.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/7476920/cl-debut-single-lifted|title=K-Pop Star CL Reaches New Heights on Debut Single 'Lifted'}}</ref> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' noted her as the \"future of Kpop in America\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://time.com/4503387/cl-america-k-pop/|title=K-POP's Next Act|website=TIME.com|access-date=2016-11-02}}</ref> On October 29, 2016, CL kicked off her first North American tour, the [[Hello Bitches Tour]], in [[New York City]]'s [[Hammerstein Ballroom]], and concluded in [[Toronto]] on November 14.<ref name=\"hbtour dates\">{{cite web|url=http://www.asianjunkie.com/2016/09/22/cl-will-embark-on-solo-tour-of-north-america-called-hello-bitches-tour-2016/|title=CL will embark on solo tour of North America, called 'HELLO BITCHES TOUR 2016'|last=|first=|date=|website=|accessdate=November 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAlongside Shaiana, she featured on [[Lil Yachty]]'s song \"Surrender\", an exclusive track off of the [[Target Corporation|Target]] deluxe edition of his album ''[[Teenage Emotions]]'', released on May 26, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allkpop.com/article/2017/05/cl-to-feature-in-lil-yachtys-new-album|title=CL to feature in Lil Yachty's new album!}}</ref> CL also recorded an original single titled \"No Better Feelin'\" for the ''[[My Little Pony: The Movie (2017 film)|My Little Pony: The Movie]]'' [[My Little Pony: The Movie (soundtrack)|soundtrack]], released on September 22, 2017.<ref name=\"mlp\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/7965887/cl-no-better-feeling-my-little-pony-movie-soundtrack|title=K-Pop Star CL Bringing 'No Better Feelin' to 'My Little Pony' Movie Soundtrack|first=Tamar|last=Herman|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=2017-09-15|accessdate=2017-09-17}}</ref> On January 4, 2018, she was reported to make her Hollywood debut as an actress in [[Peter Berg]]'s film ''[[Mile 22]]'' that stars [[Mark Wahlberg]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreanfilm.or.kr/eng/news/news.jsp?pageIndex=2&blbdComCd=601006&seq=4882&mode=VIEW&returnUrl=&searchKeyword=|title=CL Makes Hollywood Debut in MILE 22, to be Released on August 17|date=July 10, 2018|website=Korean Film}}</ref> On February 25, 2018, CL performed at the [[2018 Winter Olympics closing ceremony]] at [[Pyeongchang Olympic Stadium]], performing parts from \"[[The Baddest Female (song)|The Baddest Female]]\" and the [[2NE1]] global hit \"[[I Am the Best]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/8219143/olympics-closing-ceremony-cl-exo-performance-video|title=K-Pop Stars CL & EXO Impress at Winter Olympics Closing Ceremony|first=Tamar|last=Herman|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=February 25, 2018}}</ref> At the closing ceremony, she met with South Korean President [[Moon Jae-in]], [[First Lady of South Korea|First Lady]] [[Kim Jung-sook]], [[Exo (band)|Exo]], and U.S. [[Family of Donald Trump|First Daughter]] [[Ivanka Trump]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/IvankaTrump/status/967916873592471552|title=The world witnessed the extraordinary stories and successes of hundreds of athletes at this year's #WinterOlympics. The Olympic Closing Ceremony was an amazing tribute to all those that competed at #PyeongChang2018!pic.twitter.com/4LUrl2IKNH|last=Trump|first=Ivanka|date=2018-02-25|website=@IvankaTrump|language=en|access-date=2018-02-26}}</ref>\n\n=== 2019\u2013present: Departure from YG Entertainment and ''In the Name of Love'' ===\nOn November 8, 2019, YG Entertainment announced that CL did not renew her contract with the company.<ref>{{cite news|title=\uc528\uc5d8, \uacb0\uad6d YG \ub5a0\ub09c\ub2e4\u2026\"\uc804\uc18d\uacc4\uc57d \uc885\ub8cc \ud569\uc758..\uac01\ubcc4\ud55c \ub9c8\uc74c\uc73c\ub85c \uc751\uc6d0\"[\uacf5\uc2dd\uc785\uc7a5]|url=https://n.news.naver.com/entertain/article/009/0004460439 |website=Naver|date=November 8, 2019|accessdate=November 8, 2019|language=ko}}</ref> On December 4, right after leaving YG Entertainment, she began releasing previously unreleased tracks as her solo EP project ''In the Name of Love'' for three consecutive weeks.<ref name=\"In The Name Of Love Merch\">{{cite web|url=https://hypebae.com/2019/12/cl-in-the-name-of-love-new-album-merch-sweater-release|title=CL Launches Merch for &#039;In the Name of Love&#039;|first=Alexandra|last=Pauly|work=Hypebae|date=December 4, 2019|accessdate=December 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Musical style and influences==\nCL cites [[1TYM]] leader [[Teddy Park]], who produced much of 2NE1's music, as an influence and inspiration, as well as [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]], [[Queen(band)|Queen]], and [[Lauryn Hill]].<ref name=\"CL interview\" /><ref name=\"CL and Minzy influences\">{{cite web |url=http://star.mt.co.kr/stview.php?no=2010101315062267092&type=3 |title=\"\ubc15\ubd04\uc740 \ube44\uc698\uc138?\"..2NE1\uc774 \ubc1d\ud78c \ub864\ubaa8\ub378\uc740? |trans-title=\"Park Bom and Beyonc\u00e9?\" Who are 2NE1's role models? |language=Korean |author=Park Yeong-ung |date=October 13, 2010 |accessdate=November 13, 2010 |work=Star News |publisher=MoneyToday}}{{cite web |url=http://www.thefashionlaw.com/home/cl-talks-about-her-style-designer-friends-and-lil-kim|title=CL style inspiration for Lil' Kim|language=English |accessdate=May 14, 2016 |publisher=The Fashion Law}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{For|CL's works with 2NE1|2NE1 discography}}\n\n===Extended plays===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:6em;\" | Title\n! style=\"width:18em;\" | Details\n|-\n! scope=row | ''In the Name of Love''\n|\n*Released: December 17, 2019\n*Label: SuneV, [[Kakao M]]\n*Formats: [[Music download|digital download]], [[streaming media|streaming]]\n|}\n\n===Singles===\n\n====As lead artist====\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:12em;\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:2em;\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"4\" | Peak positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10em;\" | Sales\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:11em;\" | Album\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\" | [[Gaon Chart|KOR]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?nationGbn=T&serviceGbn=ALL|title=Gaon Digital Chart|publisher=Korea Music Content Industry Association|accessdate=March 11, 2018|language=Korean}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?nationGbn=T&serviceGbn=ALL&targetTime=23&hitYear=2013&termGbn=week|title=The Baddest Female|publisher=Korea Music Content Industry Association|accessdate=March 11, 2018}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?nationGbn=T&serviceGbn=ALL&targetTime=10&hitYear=2014&termGbn=week|title=MTBD|publisher=Korea Music Content Industry Association|accessdate=March 11, 2018}}\n* {{cite web