l Yachty]] feat. CL and Shaiana}})\n| 2017\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n| ''[[Teenage Emotions]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Dopeness\"<br>{{small|([[The Black Eyed Peas]] feat. CL)}}\n| 2018\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n| ''[[Masters of the Sun Vol. 1]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Cut It Up\"<br>{{small|(PKCZ feat. CL and [[Afrojack]])}}\n| 2019\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n| {{N/A|Non-album singles}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\" colspan=\"14\" style=\"font-size:8pt\" | \"\u2014\" denotes recordings which were not released in that country or failed to chart.<br>\"*\" denotes charts which did not exist at the time of release.\n|}\n\n===Soundtrack appearances===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"1\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"1\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"1\" | Album\n|-\n| \"No Better Feelin'\"\n| 2017\n| ''[[My Little Pony: The Movie (soundtrack)|My Little Pony: The Movie]]''\n|}\n\n==Tours==\n* ''[[Hello Bitches Tour]]'' (2016)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Organization\n! Award\n! Work\n! Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\"| 2013\n| [[Mnet 20's Choice Awards]]\n| 20's Style Award\n| Herself\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Mnet Asian Music Awards]]\n| [[Mnet Asian Music Award for Best Dance Performance|Best Dance Performance \u2013 Female Solo]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | \"[[The Baddest Female (song)|The Baddest Female]]\"\n|-\n| Song of the Year\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| MYX Philippines\n| Hottest Female Star of 2013\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Herself\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[SBS MTV|SBS MTV Best of the Best]]\n| Best Female Solo\n| rowspan=\"3\" {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2014\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Seoul Music Awards]]\n| Bonsang Awards\n| rowspan=\"2\" | \"The Baddest Female\"\n|-\n| Popularity Awards\n|-\n| YinYueTai V-Chart Awards\n| Top Female Artist (Korean)\n| rowspan=\"5\" | Herself\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| 2014\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Style Icon Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Top 10 Style Icons\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{Nom}}\n|-\n| 2016\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2019\n| [[45th People's Choice Awards]]\n| The Most Inspiring Asian Woman \n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| 29th [[Seoul Music Awards]]\n| R&B/Hip-Hop Award\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{notelist-ua}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|CL (singer)|CL}}\n* {{imdb name|id=3824666|name=CL}}\n\n{{2NE1}}\n{{CL (singer)}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:CL}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century South Korean singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century women singers]]\n[[Category:2NE1 members]]\n[[Category:School Boy Records artists]]\n[[Category:South Korean female idols]]\n[[Category:K-pop singers]]\n[[Category:South Korean hip hop singers]]\n[[Category:South Korean female pop singers]]\n[[Category:South Korean female rappers]]\n[[Category:Korean-language singers]]\n[[Category:Japanese-language singers of South Korea]]\n[[Category:English-language singers from South Korea]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Seoul]]\n[[Category:South Korean dance musicians]]\n[[Category:South Korean Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Mnet Asian Music Award winners]]\n[[Category:South Korean expatriates in France]]\n[[Category:South Korean expatriates in Japan]]\n[[Category:South Korean expatriates in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Korean name|Lee}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = CL\n| image              = CL of 2NE1 2013 (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = CL in 2013\n| native_name        = \uc774\ucc44\ub9b0\n| native_name_lang   = ko\n| birth_name         = Lee Chae-rin\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1991|02|26}}\n| birth_place        = [[Seoul]], South Korea\n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) -->\n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = South Korean\n| other_names        =\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Singer-songwriter|rapper}}\n| years_active       = 2007\u2013present\n| known_for          = \n| notable_works      = \n| awards             = \n| website            = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background       = solo_singer\n| alias            = \n| origin           = [[Seoul]], South Korea\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[K-pop]]|[[Hip hop music|hip-hop]]|[[reggae fusion]]|[[Trap music (EDM)|trap]]}}\n| instrument       = Vocals\n| label            = {{hlist|[[YG Entertainment|YG]]|[[School Boy Records|School Boy]]|SuneV}}\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[2NE1]]|[[YG Family]]}}\n}}\n| module2            = {{Infobox Korean name|child=yes\n | title   = [[Korean name]]\n | hangul  = {{linktext|\uc774|\ucc44|\ub9b0}}\n | hanja   = {{linktext|\u674e|\u5f69|\u9e9f}}\n | rr      = I Chae-rin\n | mr      = I Ch'ae-rin\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Lee Chae-rin'''  (born on February 26, 1991<ref name=\"Russell2014\">{{cite book|author=Mark Russell|title=K-Pop Now!: The Korean Music Revolution|page=77|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=etDZAwAAQBAJ|date=29 April 2014|publisher=Tuttle Publishing|isbn=978-1-4629-1411-1}}</ref>), better known by her stage name '''CL''', is a South Korean singer-songwriter, rapper and record producer.<ref name=\"Basic\">{{cite web |url=http://music.naver.com/artist/home.nhn?artistId=117570 |title=CL at Naver Music |language=Korean |work=Naver Music |publisher=NHN Corp |accessdate=November 13, 2010}}</ref> Born in [[Seoul]], South Korea, she spent much of her early life in Japan and France.<ref name=\"CL interview\">{{cite web |url=http://spn.edaily.co.kr/entertain/newsRead.asp?newsid=01230006589691544 |title=CL, \"\ub370\ubaa8 \ud14c\uc774\ud504 \ub4e4\uace0 \ubb34\uc791\uc815 YG \ubb38 \ub178\ud06c\" |trans-title=CL, \"knocked on the YG Entertainment door to hand in my demo tape\" |language=Korean |author=Park, Mi-ae |date=May 22, 2009 |accessdate=November 23, 2010 |work=eDaily SPN |publisher=eDaily }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> CL trained at [[JYP Entertainment]] before joining [[YG Entertainment]] at the age of fifteen and debuted as a member of the girl group [[2NE1]] in 2009.<ref name=\"debut with 3 members\">{{cite web |url=http://world.kbs.co.kr/english/entertainment/enter_chart_detail.htm?No=9375 |title=Female Big Bang to be Unveiled |date=March 25, 2009 |accessdate=November 13, 2010 |work=KBS Global}}</ref> Following her group taking a break, CL embarked her solo career in the United States in 2015. In 2016, 2NE1 officially disbanded and she remained a solo act under YG until her contract expired in November 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8543125/cl-leaves-k-pop-label-yg-entertainment |title=CL Leaves Longtime K-Pop Label: Report |accessdate=December 10, 2019 |work=billboard.com}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n===1991\u20132008: Early life and career beginnings===\nLee Chae-rin was born in [[Seoul]], South Korea, but spent most of her childhood living in [[Paris]], [[Tsukuba, Ibaraki|Tsukuba]], and [[Tokyo]]. When she was 13, she moved to Paris alone where she studied for two years.<ref name=\"naver.com\"/> Lee got an audition with YG Entertainment when she was 15.<ref name=\"CL interview\"/><ref name=\"naver.com\">{{cite web |url=http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=106&oid=420&aid=0000000361|title=[CL] 1\ubd80. \uc0c8\ud574 \uccab \ub0a0, \ub208\ubb3c \uc816\uc740 \uc790\uc7a5\uba74 \ub4dc\uc154\ubcf4\uc168\ub098\uc694? | language = Korean | work=OSEN |accessdate=June 13, 2013}}</ref> Her first feature on a song recording was [[Big Bang (South Korean band)|Big Bang]]'s \"Intro (Hot Issue)\" in 2007. Later that year, Lee performed for the first time on stage at [[Seoul Broadcasting System]]'s Gayo Daejeon alongside her label mates.{{citation needed|date=November 2010}} Her first credited appearance in a song was in 2008, with [[Uhm Jung-hwa]]'s \"DJ,\" in which she rapped.<ref name=\"Uhm Jung Hwa\">{{cite web |url=http://www.yesasia.com/global/uhm-jung-hwa-2008-mini-album-d-i-s-c-o/1011125524-0-0-0-en/info.html |title=Uhm Jung Hwa 2008 Mini Album \u2013 D.I.S.C.O |accessdate=November 13, 2010 |work=YesAsia.com}}</ref>\n\n===2009\u20132013: Debut with 2NE1 and solo career beginnings===\n{{main|2NE1}}\nLee took on the stage name 'CL' and was placed as the leader and main rapper of 2NE1, alongside [[Park Bom|Bom]], [[Sandara Park]] and [[Minzy]]. The group then collaborated with label-mates Big Bang for the song \"[[Lollipop (Big Bang and 2NE1 song)|Lollipop]]\" before officially debuting on [[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS]]'s ''[[The Music Trend]]'' on May 17, 2009 where they performed \"[[Fire (2NE1 song)|Fire]]\". 2NE1 achieved significant success with the number-one single \"I Don't Care\" from their first extended play, ''[[2NE1 (2009 EP)|2NE1]]'', which won them the \"Song of the Year\" award at the 2009 [[Mnet Asian Music Awards]], making them the first rookie group to win a daesang in the same year of debut.\n\nIn August 2009, she collaborated with label-mates [[G-Dragon]] and [[Teddy Park]] of [[1TYM]] for the single \"The Leaders\", featured on G-Dragon's first solo album, ''[[Heartbreaker (G-Dragon song)|Heartbreaker]]''. The same month, after the group finished with \"I Don't Care\" promotions, CL collaborated with fellow member Minzy for \"Please Don't Go,\" which charted at number six on the [[Gaon Chart]] by the end of November.<ref name=\"Gaon\">{{cite web |url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/search/list.gaon?Search_str=CL&x=23&y=20 |title=Gaon Chart Search: CL |language=Korean |accessdate=November 13, 2010 |work=Gaon Chart |publisher=Korea Music Content Industry Association}}</ref> Her first solo single, \"[[The Baddest Female]]\", was released on 28 May 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allkpop.com/article/2013/05/the-baddest-female-cl-releases-her-solo-debut-mv | title=The Baddest Female CL releases her solo debut MV | publisher=allkpop | date=2013-05-28}}</ref> For 2NE1's second album ''[[Crush (2NE1 album)|Crush]]'', CL wrote the lyrics and co-composed the music for the tracks \"Crush\", \"If I Were You\", and \"Baby I Miss You\". She also wrote the lyrics for her solo track \"MTBD\", as well as the track \"Scream\".<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/6281868/cl-solo-america-scooter-braun-2ne1 \"K-Pop Superstar CL to Enter America With Scooter Braun\"], ''Billboard'', 16 October 2014. Accessed 13 October 2015.</ref>\n\n===2014\u20132019: Stand-alone singles and featured appearances===\n[[File:CL at Twin Towers Alive Event Malaysia.jpg|thumb|200px|CL in 2013]]\nIn October 2014, it was announced that CL was planning to debut as a solo artist the following year in the United States, teaming up with [[Scooter Braun]] as her manager.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allkpop.com/article/2014/10/2ne1s-cl-confirmed-to-make-her-us-debut-as-a-solo-artist|title=2NE1's CL confirmed to make her U.S. debut as a solo artist}}</ref> In May 2015, she featured in [[Diplo]]'s single \"[[Doctor Pepper (song)|Doctor Pepper]]\", alongside [[Riff Raff (rapper)|Riff Raff]] and [[OG Maco]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hypebeast.com/2015/8/diplo-featuring-cl-riff-raff-og-maco-doctor-pepper-music-video|title=Diplo Featuring CL, RiFF RAFF & OG Maco \"Doctor Pepper\" Music Video}}</ref> In November 2015, CL released her first single \"[[Hello Bitches]]\", as a teaser for her upcoming EP ''Lifted''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fuse.tv/2015/09/cl-lifted-english-ep|title=CL Preps Debut English EP 'Lifted' for Fall|access-date=2016-08-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/6670465/diplo-cl-birthday-one-kpop|title=Diplo Talks K-Pop & New Songs Recorded With CL in 'Time' Interview|access-date=2016-08-18}}</ref> The lead single, \"[[Lifted (CL song)|Lifted]]\" was released on August 19, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.allkpop.com/article/2016/08/cl-gets-lifted-in-her-newest-solo-mv|title=CL gets 'Lifted' in her newest solo MV! {{!}} allkpop.com|access-date=2016-08-18}}</ref> The song appeared in the Top 30 of iTunes\u2019 Hip-Hop/Rap chart within three hours of being released, peaking at 21.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/7476920/cl-debut-single-lifted|title=K-Pop Star CL Reaches New Heights on Debut Single 'Lifted'}}</ref> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' noted her as the \"future of Kpop in America\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://time.com/4503387/cl-america-k-pop/|title=K-POP's Next Act|website=TIME.com|access-date=2016-11-02}}</ref> On October 29, 2016, CL kicked off her first North American tour, the [[Hello Bitches Tour]], in [[New York City]]'s [[Hammerstein Ballroom]], and concluded in [[Toronto]] on November 14.<ref name=\"hbtour dates\">{{cite web|url=http://www.asianjunkie.com/2016/09/22/cl-will-embark-on-solo-tour-of-north-america-called-hello-bitches-tour-2016/|title=CL will embark on solo tour of North America, called 'HELLO BITCHES TOUR 2016'|last=|first=|date=|website=|accessdate=November 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAlongside Shaiana, she featured on [[Lil Yachty]]'s song \"Surrender\", an exclusive track off of the [[Target Corporation|Target]] deluxe edition of his album ''[[Teenage Emotions]]'', released on May 26, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allkpop.com/article/2017/05/cl-to-feature-in-lil-yachtys-new-album|title=CL to feature in Lil Yachty's new album!}}</ref> CL also recorded an original single titled \"No Better Feelin'\" for the ''[[My Little Pony: The Movie (2017 film)|My Little Pony: The Movie]]'' [[My Little Pony: The Movie (soundtrack)|soundtrack]], released on September 22, 2017.<ref name=\"mlp\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/7965887/cl-no-better-feeling-my-little-pony-movie-soundtrack|title=K-Pop Star CL Bringing 'No Better Feelin' to 'My Little Pony' Movie Soundtrack|first=Tamar|last=Herman|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=2017-09-15|accessdate=2017-09-17}}</ref> On January 4, 2018, she was reported to make her Hollywood debut as an actress in [[Peter Berg]]'s film ''[[Mile 22]]'' that stars [[Mark Wahlberg]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreanfilm.or.kr/eng/news/news.jsp?pageIndex=2&blbdComCd=601006&seq=4882&mode=VIEW&returnUrl=&searchKeyword=|title=CL Makes Hollywood Debut in MILE 22, to be Released on August 17|date=July 10, 2018|website=Korean Film}}</ref> On February 25, 2018, CL performed at the [[2018 Winter Olympics closing ceremony]] at [[Pyeongchang Olympic Stadium]], performing parts from \"[[The Baddest Female (song)|The Baddest Female]]\" and the [[2NE1]] global hit \"[[I Am the Best]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/8219143/olympics-closing-ceremony-cl-exo-performance-video|title=K-Pop Stars CL & EXO Impress at Winter Olympics Closing Ceremony|first=Tamar|last=Herman|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=February 25, 2018}}</ref> At the closing ceremony, she met with South Korean President [[Moon Jae-in]], [[First Lady of South Korea|First Lady]] [[Kim Jung-sook]], [[Exo (band)|Exo]], and U.S. [[Family of Donald Trump|First Daughter]] [[Ivanka Trump]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/IvankaTrump/status/967916873592471552|title=The world witnessed the extraordinary stories and successes of hundreds of athletes at this year's #WinterOlympics. The Olympic Closing Ceremony was an amazing tribute to all those that competed at #PyeongChang2018!pic.twitter.com/4LUrl2IKNH|last=Trump|first=Ivanka|date=2018-02-25|website=@IvankaTrump|language=en|access-date=2018-02-26}}</ref>\n\n=== 2019\u2013present: Departure from YG Entertainment and ''In the Name of Love'' ===\nOn November 8, 2019, YG Entertainment announced that CL did not renew her contract with the company.<ref>{{cite news|title=\uc528\uc5d8, \uacb0\uad6d YG \ub5a0\ub09c\ub2e4\u2026\"\uc804\uc18d\uacc4\uc57d \uc885\ub8cc \ud569\uc758..\uac01\ubcc4\ud55c \ub9c8\uc74c\uc73c\ub85c \uc751\uc6d0\"[\uacf5\uc2dd\uc785\uc7a5]|url=https://n.news.naver.com/entertain/article/009/0004460439 |website=Naver|date=November 8, 2019|accessdate=November 8, 2019|language=ko}}</ref> On December 4, right after leaving YG Entertainment, she began releasing previously unreleased tracks as her solo EP project ''In the Name of Love'' for three consecutive weeks.<ref name=\"In The Name Of Love Merch\">{{cite web|url=https://hypebae.com/2019/12/cl-in-the-name-of-love-new-album-merch-sweater-release|title=CL Launches Merch for &#039;In the Name of Love&#039;|first=Alexandra|last=Pauly|work=Hypebae|date=December 4, 2019|accessdate=December 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Musical style and influences==\nCL cites [[1TYM]] leader [[Teddy Park]], who produced much of 2NE1's music, as an influence and inspiration, as well as [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]], [[Queen(band)|Queen]], and [[Lauryn Hill]].<ref name=\"CL interview\" /><ref name=\"CL and Minzy influences\">{{cite web |url=http://star.mt.co.kr/stview.php?no=2010101315062267092&type=3 |title=\"\ubc15\ubd04\uc740 \ube44\uc698\uc138?\"..2NE1\uc774 \ubc1d\ud78c \ub864\ubaa8\ub378\uc740? |trans-title=\"Park Bom and Beyonc\u00e9?\" Who are 2NE1's role models? |language=Korean |author=Park Yeong-ung |date=October 13, 2010 |accessdate=November 13, 2010 |work=Star News |publisher=MoneyToday}}{{cite web |url=http://www.thefashionlaw.com/home/cl-talks-about-her-style-designer-friends-and-lil-kim|title=CL style inspiration for Lil' Kim|language=English |accessdate=May 14, 2016 |publisher=The Fashion Law}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{For|CL's works with 2NE1|2NE1 discography}}\n\n===Extended plays===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:6em;\" | Title\n! style=\"width:18em;\" | Details\n|-\n! scope=row | ''In the Name of Love''\n|\n*Released: December 17, 2019\n*Label: SuneV, [[Kakao M]]\n*Formats: [[Music download|digital download]], [[streaming media|streaming]]\n|}\n\n===Singles===\n\n====As lead artist====\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:12em;\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:2em;\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"4\" | Peak positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10em;\" | Sales\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:11em;\" | Album\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\" | [[Gaon Chart|KOR]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?nationGbn=T&serviceGbn=ALL|title=Gaon Digital Chart|publisher=Korea Music Content Industry Association|accessdate=March 11, 2018|language=Korean}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?nationGbn=T&serviceGbn=ALL&targetTime=23&hitYear=2013&termGbn=week|title=The Baddest Female|publisher=Korea Music Content Industry Association|accessdate=March 11, 2018}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?nationGbn=T&serviceGbn=ALL&targetTime=10&hitYear=2014&termGbn=week|title=MTBD|publisher=Korea Music Content Industry Association|accessdate=March 11, 2018}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?serviceGbn=S1020&termGbn=week&hitYear=2015&targetTime=24&nationGbn=E|title=Doctor Pepper|publisher=Korea Music Content Industry Association|accessdate=March 11, 2018}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?nationGbn=T&serviceGbn=ALL&targetTime=51&hitYear=2015&termGbn=week|title=Hello Bitches|publisher=Korea Music Content Industry Association|accessdate=March 11, 2018}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?nationGbn=T&serviceGbn=ALL&targetTime=49&hitYear=2019&t